page.title: 14 Natural Landscapes
page.content: For the interested geographer an intriguing dried up stream bed runs through Denstead Wood.It evinces a well formed dry river valley.Although on a small scale this shows all the classical geographical signs.Higher up its course it meanders in a shallow trough about 8 metres wide by 9 to 15 metres high.This valley reaches a peak further down the course when it reaches a depth of about 25 metres and a width at the bottom of 12 to 15 metres.It is surprising to note that these features have been formed by a river that does not appear to have run all year.It was dry when we visited it in June but the leaves and branches found on the bends were recent and considerable in amount,suggesting that it was fairly full for quite a few months of the year.
